A user wants to access the website by typing [www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com) in a browser.

First, the DNS translates the domain name [www.foobar.com](http://www.foobar.com) to the server IP address 8.8.8.8. After getting the IP address, the user's computer sends an HTTP request to the server.

The server contains Nginx, an application server, the application files, and a MySQL database.

Nginx works as the web server. It receives requests from users and forwards them to the application server when needed.

The application server runs the application code and processes the user's requests. If data is needed, it communicates with the MySQL database.

The MySQL database stores and manages the application's data such as user information and website content.

A server is a computer that provides services to other computers called clients.

The role of the domain name is to provide a human-readable name instead of using an IP address.

The www record is an A record that points to the server IP address 8.8.8.8.

The server communicates with the user's computer using the TCP/IP protocol and HTTP requests.

This infrastructure has some problems. It has a Single Point of Failure (SPOF) because everything is running on one server. If the server goes down, the website becomes unavailable.

Another problem is downtime during maintenance. If the server or web server needs to be restarted when deploying new code, the website may become unavailable for some time.

It also cannot scale easily because a single server may not be able to handle a large amount of incoming traffic



